operation. The knowledge goes beyond the traditional process engineering field by applying the same principles, to biomedical processes, energy production and management of environmental issues. The book explains all the determinations in the "chemical systems" or "process systems", starting from the beginning of the processes, going through the intricate interdependency of the process stages, analyzing the hardware components of a control system and ending with the design of an appropriate control system for a process parameter or a whole process. The book is first addressed to the students and graduates of the departments of Chemical or Process Engineering. Second, to the chemical or process engineers in all industries or research and development centers, because they will notice the resemblance in approach from the system and control point of view, between different fields which might seem far from each other, but share the same control philosophy.  aIssued also in print.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aChemical engineering. 0aChemical process control. 0aProcess control. 4aAutomatisierungstechnik. 4aChemieingenieurwesen. 4aProzessleittechnik. 4aProzesstechnik. 4aTechnische Chemie. 4aVerfahrenstechnik. 7aTechnology & Engineering / Chemical & Biochemical.2bisacsh  aAutomation Technology.  aAutomation.  aChemical Plant.  aControl Engineering.  aControl Panel.  aController.  aMeasuring, Regulating, Control.  aMemory Programmable Control.  aProcess Control.1 aAgachi, Paul Șerban, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCristea, Mircea Vasile, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut1 aCsavdari, Alexandra Ana, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut1 aSzilagyi, Botond, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/rel